---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal">
  <h1>Limits</h1>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Credibility close — never oversell. Name the trade-offs plainly.</p>
    <p>
      The goal is not to pretend build-time disappears. The goal is to show
      which decisions can now move closer to the browser.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Support &amp; progressive enhancement</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      📊 <span>A lot of this is </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >usable today</span
      ><span> — some parts still need care</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🛟 <span>Lean on </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">@supports</span
      ><span> — enhance, don't require</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🧱 <span>Sensible </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">fallbacks</span
      ><span> first, modern layer on top</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Tie back to the honest-support slides in section 7. The pattern is always
      the same: fallback first, modern CSS as enhancement.
    </p>
    <p>
      Say it: a design system can't blindly assume the newest browser — but it
      can reward it.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is how we get the benefits without making the baseline experience
      fragile.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Enhance, don't require</span> 🛟
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="enhance.css">
    <code style="font-size: 0.7em" is:raw class="language-scss">
    /* sensible baseline everyone gets */
    article {
        background: #f4f4f4;
        color: #1a1a1a;
    }

    /* reward modern browsers */
    @supports (background: light-dark(white, black)) {
        :root { color-scheme: light dark; }
        article {
            background: light-dark(white, oklch(0.2 0 0));
            color: light-dark(oklch(0.2 0 0), white);
        }
    }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      One concrete example beats a paragraph. The baseline is never broken; the
      modern path is additive.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is the responsible way to use newer CSS in a design system: not as a
      cliff, but as a layer.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal-sub-section">
  <h2>What about AI?</h2>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Everyone expects the AI moment — make it serve the talk's thesis instead.
    </p>
    <p>
      Two sides in two slides: the risk (unsteered, AI gives you the average of
      the web) and the opportunity (AI as an accelerator once you know where
      you're going).
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">How modern is your AI's CSS?</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      ✨ <span>Newer models </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >can speak modern CSS</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🧲 <span>Vague prompts get </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >the average of the web</span
      ><span> — still build-time</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      📅 <span>Browser support moves </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >faster than training cutoffs</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Be fair to the models: recent ones know color-mix(), light-dark() and
      friends perfectly well. The problem isn't knowledge.
    </p>
    <p>
      It's gravity: with a vague prompt you get the average of the published web
      — and that average is still build-time pipelines and precomputed shades.
      Modern CSS is in there, but it's not the default unless you ask.
    </p>
    <p>
      Second gap: support tables move faster than training data — if() in
      Chromium 137+ is younger than most cutoffs. "What's usable today" is still
      your call.
    </p>
    <p>
      Which is the talk's thesis from another angle: knowing what the browser
      does natively is exactly how you steer AI toward runtime CSS.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">AI as an accelerator</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      🔁 <span>Migrating </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >Sass → modern CSS</span
      ><span> is mechanical work AI is good at</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🛟 <span>Generating </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        ><code>@supports</code> fallbacks</span
      ><span> &amp; support checks</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      👀 <span>You stay the </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >reviewer</span
      ><span> — the browser is the judge</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Flip side: once you know where you're going, AI is a great pair of hands.
      Translating Sass loops into color-mix() and clamp() is mechanical work it
      does well.
    </p>
    <p>
      Same for the boring-but-vital parts: @supports fallbacks, checking support
      tables, porting a theme to light-dark().
    </p>
    <p>
      Declarative, toolchain-free CSS is easier to generate and easier to verify
      — you review it, the browser judges it. Which leads straight into the
      closing line.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="center" autoplay timing="550">
  <h2 class="main-gradient" style="margin-block-end: 0.3em">
    The browser is part of the build tool now
  </h2>
  <p-fragment>
    <p style="font-size: 0.7em; opacity: 0.8;">
      Less precomputed CSS. More runtime CSS.
    </p>
  </p-fragment>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Full circle to the opening question: "what if the browser could do most of
      this?" — now it can do a lot more than it used to.
    </p>
    <p>
      I slightly soften the original line here: not "the browser replaces the
      build tool", but "the browser becomes part of the system".
    </p>
    <p>This is the line they leave with. Don't rush it.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
